TY  - JOUR
AU  - Blinder, Alan S.
AU  - Choi, Don H.
T1  - A Shred of Evidence on Theories of Wage Stickiness*
PY  - 1990
Y1  - 1990/11/01
DO  - 10.2307/2937882
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 105
IS  - 4
SP  - 1003
EP  - 1015
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - A small interview survey was undertaken to see how actual wage-setters would react to the central ideas of several economic theories of wage stickiness. Wage cuts were surprisingly prevalent in recent years, despite the booming economy. The strongest finding was that managers believe that perceptions of fairness play a major motivational role in labor markets and that a “fair” wage policy is a good deal more complicated than simply not cutting wages. We also found substantial evidence for money illusion and against the adverse-selection version of the efficiency wage model.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2937882
ER  - 



